What is the difference between>,>>

This is a very important small concept — many students lose marks here. Let’s make it crystal clear.
🧠 Difference between > and >>
🔹 1. > (Overwrite)

echo "Hello" > file.txt

👉 Meaning:

    Creates file (if not exists)

    Replaces entire content if file already exists

📌 Result:

Hello

🔹 2. >> (Append)

echo "Hello" >> file.txt

👉 Meaning:

    Creates file (if not exists)

    Adds content at the end

📌 Result:

(previous content)
Hello

🔥 SIMPLE EXAMPLE
Step 1:

echo "Line 1" > file.txt

👉 file.txt:

Line 1

Step 2:

echo "Line 2" >> file.txt

👉 file.txt:

Line 1
Line 2

Step 3:

echo "Line 3" > file.txt

👉 file.txt:

Line 3

❌ Old content gone!
🎯 In your case (VERY IMPORTANT)
❌ This:

echo "This is from main branch" > README.txt

👉 Deletes everything and writes only this line
✅ This:

echo "This is from main branch" >> README.txt

👉 Adds line to existing file (correct for Git experiment)
🧠 Easy Memory Trick

👉 > → Replace
👉 >> → Add
🎯 Exam Answer (short)

👉
“> overwrites the file, whereas >> appends content to the existing file.”
⚠️ Important in Experiment 2

If you use > by mistake:
❌ Conflict may not occur
❌ Previous content lost

👉 So ALWAYS use:

>> 

