Can we use cat command to resolve the conflict?

Short answer: ❌ No — cat does NOT resolve conflicts.
But… ✅ you can use it as a helper. Let me explain clearly.
🧠 What is cat?

cat README.txt

👉 It just displays file content
👉 It does NOT edit or fix anything
💥 During Merge Conflict

File will look like:

<<<<<<< HEAD
This is from main branch
=======
This is from feature branch
>>>>>>> feature-branch

👉 This means:

    Above ======= → main branch

    Below ======= → feature branch

❌ Can cat resolve this?

👉 NO ❌
Because:

    cat cannot edit file

    It only shows content

✅ Correct Way to Resolve Conflict
🔹 Step 1: Open file (IMPORTANT)

Use any editor:

    Notepad

    VS Code

👉 Or even Git Bash with:

nano README.txt

🔹 Step 2: Manually fix

Change this:

<<<<<<< HEAD
This is from main branch
=======
This is from feature branch
>>>>>>> feature-branch

👉 To this:

This is from main branch
This is from feature branch

🔹 Step 3: Save file
🔹 Step 4: Finalize

git add README.txt
git commit -m "Resolved conflict"

🧠 Where cat is useful?

👉 You can use it to see the conflict

cat README.txt

👉 Helps you understand before editing
💡 Smart Trick (Exam)

You can say:

👉
“cat command is used to view the conflict, but conflict resolution is done manually by editing the file.”

🔥 Examiner will be impressed.
🚀 Pro Tip (Advanced but easy)

If you want quick resolution:
Keep current branch version:

git checkout --ours README.txt

Keep feature branch version:

git checkout --theirs README.txt

Then:

git add README.txt
git commit

🎯 Final Answer (Exam)

👉
“No, cat cannot resolve merge conflicts. It is only used to display file contents. Conflicts must be resolved manually by editing the file.”

